We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to submit all the MOA of the PPAs to COA for further evaluation;

The MA to coordinate with the MPDC and the Municipal Treasurer for the determination of the SA and purpose of the fund received in item 2;

Transfer the interest income, net of taxes, reported under item 11 to the GF;

Present the description of the projects under items 8 and 9; and

Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused balance to the SA.

We recommended, and the OMA agreed to:
Continuously trace back prior years’ records pertaining to the acquisition dates and/or recording of the various PPE accounts amounting to ₱136.975 million;
Effect the necessary adjustments for the recognition of the prior years’ depreciation and the corresponding accumulated depreciation of various PPE accounts amounting to ₱136.975 million, taking into consideration the cost, year, month of purchase/completion, and useful life. Thereafter, provide for the annual depreciation, if applicable;
Adjust the noted net overstatement of total depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation of ₱4.855 million and ₱113,007.03 million in the books of accounts, respectively, and furnish journal entry vouchers to COA Office;
For consistency on the estimated useful life, revisit Annex A of COA Circular No. 2003-007 and DPWH DO No. 176 s. 2015, and make necessary corrections on its depreciation schedule; and
Moving forward, carefully review the computation of depreciation to avoid misstatements of depreciation expenses, particularly fully depreciated assets.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Consistently apply the Perpetual Inventory Method (Asset Method) for all inventoriable items in accordance with the NGAS Manual, particularly in the adoption of the Moving Average Method in inventory costing, as prescribed, with its own disclosed accounting policies as stated in the Notes to FS;
Record the yearend unused AFs amounting to ₱27,572.10;
Recognize AFs as Inventories upon purchase, and prepare SSMI reports to support proper liquidation and accounting entries;
Ensure drugs and medicines distributed to constituents are documented, including preparation of RIS and distribution lists for transparency and audit trail;
Enforce timely preparation and submission of FCRs before closing of books; and
Correctly classify SEP under their appropriate SEP accounts and rectify misclassifications through adjusting entries.

